Introduction¶

Wine certification is generally assessed by physicochemical and sensory tests . Physicochemical laboratory tests routinely used to characterize wine include determination of density, alcohol or pH values, while sensory tests rely mainly on human experts. It should be stressed that taste is the least understood of the human senses thus wine classification is a difficult task. Moreover, There are numerous factors that may impact the quality of red wine and white wine.so it will be a gigantic challenge to Find the biggest contributors.

This report is organized as follows:

  • Overview section describes the dataset used and the features in this dataset.
  • Data Preparation section covers data cleaning and data preparation steps.
  • Data Exploration section explores dataset features and their inter-relationships.
  • Statistical Modeling and Performance Evaluation section fits multiple linear regression models and performs diagnostic checks.
  • Summary and Conclusions section provides a summary of our methodology and presents our findings.
  • Reference

Overview¶

Data source¶

For this project,the datasets that we choose are from the UCI Machine Learning Repository which concatenate two datasets'winequality-white.csvandwinequality-red.csv` into one. Those datasets are provided to test more computationally demanding machine learning algorithms that is useful for our goal. It has been selected from Wine Quality Data Set(at https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/Wine+Quality) by Paulo Cortez,António Cerdeira, Fernando Almeida,Telmo Matos,José Reis. Data repository available on the https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0167923609001377?via%3Dihub (November 2009)

Project Objective¶

Our aim is to determine which physicochemical input have the most impact on quality of wine, being affected positively or negatively in what degree.We analyse by selected variables due to various factors to see which one has the main effect on wine.

Response variable¶

Output variable (based on sensory data):

  • quality (score between 0 and 10)

We choose the only output quality as our response /target feature. It is a numerical integer which is able to be set as the actual quality that built up graphs and linear regression models for comparison with those 11 descriptive features. Quality of wine: quality measure in wine

Descriptive Features¶

  • fixed acidity
  • volatile acidity
  • citric acid
  • residual sugar
  • chlorides
  • free sulfur dioxide
  • total sulfur dioxide
  • density
  • pH
  • sulphates
  • alcohol

#specifying the attribute names
attributeNames = [
   'fixed acidity',
   'volatile acidity',
   'citric acid',
   'residual sugar',
   'chlorides',
   'free sulfur dioxide',
   'total sulfur dioxide',
   'density',
   'pH',
   'sulphates',
   'alcohol',
   'quality',
    
]
#Read in data
winequality_white = pd.read_csv('winequality-white.csv',sep=';',names = attributeNames)
winequality_red = pd.read_csv('winequality-red.csv',sep=';',names = attributeNames)

#Join the two datasets together
winequality = pd.concat([winequality_white,winequality_red])

#Display randomly selected 10 rows
winequality.sample(10,random_state=999)

Fixing Column Names¶

Some column names contain a space, which can be problematic when modeling. Basically, when we write the regression formula. So, we modify the column names so that the space are replaced with an underscore sign.

In [54]:
winequality.rename(columns={'fixed acidity':'fixed_acidity',
                        'volatile acidity':'volatile_aciditys',
                        'citric acid':'citric_acid',
                        'residual sugar':'residual_sugar',
                           'free sulfur dioxide':'free_sulfur_dioxide',
                           'total sulfur dioxide':'total_sulfur_dioxide'}, inplace = True)

Statistical Modeling and Performance Evaluation¶

Full Model¶

We begin by fitting a multiple linear regression that predicts the relationship between each indenpendent variable to dependentquality using all of the avaliable features. We call this the full model. First let's take a quick peak at the clean data.

Models:

  • quality and fixed acidity
  • quality and volatile acidity
  • quality and citric acid
  • quality and residual sugar
  • quality and chlorides
  • quality and free sulfur dioxide
  • quality and total sulfur dioxide
  • quality and density
  • quality and pH
  • quality and sulphates
  • quality and alcohol -quality and sum
  • Full Model
  • Backwards Variable Selection

def plot_line(axis, slope, intercept, **kargs):
    xmin, xmax = axis.get_xlim()
    plt.plot([xmin, xmax], [xmin*slope+intercept, xmax*slope+intercept], **kargs)
  

def plot_line(axis, slope, intercept, **kargs):
    xmin, xmax = axis.get_xlim()
    plt.plot([xmin, xmax], [xmin*slope+intercept, xmax*slope+intercept], **kargs)

y=winequality['fixed_acidity']

plt.ylabel('quality')
plt.show()

Sum and quality¶

In [119]:
winequality=winequality.dropna(axis=0,how='any')

                        'volatile acidity':'volatile_aciditys',
                        'citric acid':'citric_acid',
                        'residual sugar':'residual_sugar',
                           'free sulfur dioxide':'free_sulfur_dioxide',
                           'total sulfur dioxide':'total_sulfur_dioxide'}, inplace = True)

winequality['sum'] = winequality.apply(lambda x: x.sum()- x['quality'], axis = 1)

formula_string = "quality ~ sum"
model = sm.formula.ols(formula=formula_string, data = winequality)
model_fitted = model.fit()

Backwards Variable Selection¶

We now perform backwards variable selection using p-values.

In [124]:
## create the patsy model desc from formula
my_linreg_patsy = patsy.ModelDesc.from_formula(formula_string)
###
# initialize variable-selected fit to full model
linreg_fit = model_fitted
#########
## do backwards elimination using p-values
p_val_cutoff = 0.05
for i in range(len(linreg_fit.model.exog_names)):
    pval_series = linreg_fit.pvalues.copy()
    pval_series.sort_values(ascending=False, inplace=True)
    term = pval_series.index[0]
    pval = pval_series[0]
    if (pval < p_val_cutoff):
        break
    print(f"iteration: {i}, removing term: {term}, p-value: {pval:.3f}")
    terms = term.split(':')
    if (len(terms) == 1): ## this is a main effect term
        my_linreg_patsy.rhs_termlist.remove(patsy.Term([patsy.EvalFactor(term)]))    
    else: ## this is an interaction term
        my_linreg_patsy.rhs_termlist.remove(patsy.Term([patsy.EvalFactor(terms[0]), patsy.EvalFactor(terms[1])]))    
    linreg_fit = smf.ols(formula = my_linreg_patsy, data = df).fit()
#########

###
## this is the clean fit after backwards elimination
model_reduced_fitted = smf.ols(formula = my_linreg_patsy, data = winequality).fit()
###
    
#########
print("***")
print(model_reduced_fitted.summary())
print("***")

print(f"Regression F-distribution p-value: {model_reduced_fitted.f_pvalue:.4f}")
print(f"Regression R-squared: {model_reduced_fitted.rsquared:.4f}")
print(f"Regression Adjusted R-squared: {model_reduced_fitted.rsquared_adj:.4f}")

Summary and Conclusions¶

1 Abstract With Portuguess wine sell increasingly enjoyed by market, red and white wine becomes much popular among consumers.In this project, we need to find out how does wine preferences affected by what physicochemical features.Although the taste of wine quality is subjective, it is impacted by some physicochemical and sensory tests objectively.Our goal is to find out how those 11 given input attributes affect the output of wine quality in what degree.We put those 11 independent variable in x-axis and one dependent target variable in y-axis, compare each feature to quality by putting the actual data into the modelling, for checking how does the actual data near the regression line in what situation and the residual value to see what actual feature is the most relativity would predict the future as well.

2 Relative Work 2.1 Part1-Data Cleaning and transformation

The datasets folder in UCI repository just contains two file, one for red wine another for wine wine datasets.We concatenate them into one then analyse it.There we read it from csv file with seperator ‘;’.There are 12 columns in total, 11 attributes are independent and continuous numeric value, 1 explanatory value is integer.All of them are numeric, so we don’t need to worry about categorical data.We check each variables’ maximum, minimum and mean value by using max(),min(),mean() respectively.

2.1.1 Data type transformation We convert data type “object” to “numeric”. 2.1.2 Missing Value We need to check whether there is missing value. In our datasets, there is no missing value inside.For example, we use 2.1.3 Outliers We need to check whether there any outliers inside the datasets is the same as UCI repository datasets description.In that datasets description, there is no actual description or limitations. But I still identify with common sense such as pH is from 1-14, if it is 15,I would replace it with mean value.And if the quality is not integer but continuous value also needed to be reset.In our datasets, there is no outliers.

Part2 - Data Exploration

.2.1 Single comparison We create box plot, density plot, histogram for single variable comparison to see its 2.2.2 Multivariate Visualisation comparison We generate scatterplot, hex bin scatterplot for multiple/different variable compare with quality. Percentile (median,Q1,Q3,IQR,max,min) Q1 presents 25% percentile, median represents the 50% percentile, Q3 represents 75% percentile.Those percentile are easily to observe the variance.In our dataset, Q1 =5.0, Q2 = Median =6.0, Q3 = 6.0, IQR =1.0, min = 3.0, max =9.0.

Part3 -Linear Regression Modelling

2.3.1Design thought and principle For checking the regression result, we need to check residuals initially, which are the leftovers from the model fit -the least square, to determine the relativity between the actual to predicted value, based on the fomula yˆ = β 0 + β 1 x . About residuals, there are three limitations needed to be satisfied in the regression model. First, the relationship between the explanatory and the response variable should be linear. Second, the residuals should be nearly normal checked using a histogram that show in each single feature modelling. Third, the variability of points around the least squares line should be roughly constant as well. Thus, we need to check each residuals is normal distributed in histogram in each modelling that is able to be used for regression analysis.Finally to do reduced model, full model diagnostic checks then find out the result.

2.3.2 Statistical Modelling and Performance Evaluation We build up 11 models for each independent features in terms of fixed acidity, volatile acidity, citric acid, residual sugar, chlorides, free sulfur dioxide, total sulfur dioxide, density, pH, sulphates,alcohol and quality.And sum of those 11 features to quality, full model and backwards variable selection. In 11 independent features to quality regression model, compare to each R-Sqaure, its shown as below:
fixed acidity and quality : 0.006 volatile acidity and quality : 0.064 citric acid and quality: 0.004 residual sugar and quality: 0.002 chlorides and quality: 0.038 free sulfur dioxide and quality：0.002 total sulfur dioxide, and quality：0.004 density and quality：0.094 pH and quality：0.001 sulphates and quality：0.001 alcohol and quality：0.200 From above, the higher R-square represents much relativity to predicted quality. So we can observe that, chlorides, density and alcohol takes up the top 3 relevance in 3.8%,9.4% and 20% respectively. And residual sugar, free sulfur dioxide, and total sulfur dioxide should be abandom from the regression modelling due to right-skewed residuals distribution.

2.3.3 Full Model The reduced Model shows there is a positive linear relationship between the actual quality and predicted, and the model is reasonably fitted. The adjusted R-Squared value is 0.289, meaning that 28.9% of the variance is described in the model. Regarding to coefficients, there are quite a few p-values that are not significant, that is residual sugar, free sulfur dioxide, total sulfur dioxide. Because in those residuals histogram they don’t have normal distribution which cannot put into regression modelling strictly speaking. The p-values for the coefficients of the health variables were largly significant, which shows the relationship is positively relevant.

2.3.4 Full Model Diagnostic Checks From the scatterplot, it is observed that the majority of the plots reside between -1.2 and 1.5 in y-axis,which makes the model valid. However there are some outliers, the largest outlier is a negative residual between 4 and 6 along the x-axis and it is just above 2 on the y-axis, the second largest outlier is a positive residual below 5 along the x-axis. Apart from these outliers, the points are generally centred on 0. As a result only 1 variables were used -alcohol. The p-value of the reduced model is 0.0, meaning the coefficients used are significant.

2.3.4 Backwards Variable Selection The backwards variable selection shows there is a positive linear relationship between the actual quality and predicted, and this selection is non-reasonably fitted. The adjusted R-Squared value is 0.001, meaning that 0.1% of the variance is described in the reduced model. Regarding to coefficients, there are quite a few p-values that are significant, which means that they are irrelevant to the predicted regression.

2.3.5 Residuals From all of the 11 features of histogram, the residuals are approximately normal distributed, except residual sugar, free sulfur dioxide, and total sulfur dioxide are right-skewed distributed, which means that they are not suitable for building up the regression model, but the rest of the 8 features can be. The full model and the reduced model have similar residuals. The the most significant outliers in this model are in between the same intervals as the full model 5, there are some positive residuals and 8, there is one major negative residual.

2.3.6 Probability Plot From all of the 11 features of probability plot, all of the observed value are closed to its theoretical quantities, that means the probabilities are valid.

3 Conclusion To conclude, no matter what is white or red wine, the quality is mostly depends on chlorides, density and alcohol that indirectly affect the customer's taste in some degree due to its subjectivity. But we believe that it is also a very good reference to help the wine manufacturer devotes more marketing campaign to know customers’ preference by those features emphatically, it would help to sell more products and earn better reputation to higher quality mark.
